alised and sustained by using examples of our lived experience.Key FeaturesCritically re-engages with the canonical theories of biopolitics from Foucault, Agamben and EspositoIntroduces new philosophical voices into the discussion of biopolitics: Nancy, Badiou and LefortExplicates the historical background of the contemporary critique of biopoliticsInterprets the current crisis of liberal democracy through a biopolitical lens, and suggests possibilities for overcoming it  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBiopoliticsxPhilosophy. 0aBiopolitics. 0aDemocracy. 4aPolitics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311078042040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147444936640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474449366423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474449366/original  a978-3-11-078042-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK